{
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionThe advent of Large Language Models (LLMs) has ushered in a transformative era in artificial intelligence, particularly within the realm of natural language processing [1].",
    "These sophisticated models, exemplified by the Generative Pre-trained Transformer (GPT) series, have demonstrated unparalleled proficiency in generating text that is not only coherent but contextually advanced and relevant [2].",
    "Trained on extensive and diverse datasets, LLMs have shown remarkable versatility, tackling a spectrum of tasks from basic text completion to addressing complex, multifaceted queries [2].",
    "However, amidst these advancements, a critical challenge has persistently overshadowed their utility -the accurate and reliable retrieval of information, and this challenge is not merely a technical hurdle, but a fundamental requisite for the effective application of LLMs across a myriad of sectors, where precision in information retrieval is nonnegotiable [3,4].Historically, efforts to enhance the information retrieval accuracy of LLMs have been marked by significant but insufficient progress.",
    "Past studies primarily focused on refining training methodologies and optimizing model architectures to mitigate the impact of biases inherent in the training datasets [5,6]."
  ]
}